'''Illusionistic tradition''' is a style of [[theatre]] that was created in [[Italy]] during the [[Renaissance]]. Its focus was primarily centered on grandiose spectacle in theatrical performance. Stages made use of [[Italianate]] scenery, including [[Proscenium|Proscenium arch]], [[Perspective (visual)|perspective]], border flats, and a [[Rake (theatre)|raked stage]] to create a visual image that had never before been used.

